It is not improbable that Rogers caught the mould of his blank verse from the copy rather than from the model. In the matter of style—as Flaubert has said—the second-bests are often the better teachers. More is to be learned from La Fontaine and Gautier than from Moliere and Victor Hugo.

Many art—books, many books addressed specially to the connoisseur‚ as well as most of those invalu— able volumes no gentleman's library should be with- out, found their places on Rogers's hospitable shelves. Of such, it is needless to speak3 nor, in this place, is it necessary to deal with his finished and amiable, but not very vigorous or vital poetry. A parting word may, however, be devoted to the poet himself.
